ce:section.ce:para:
CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposites with different amounts of CQDs were prepared via a microwave-assisted hydrothermal method from ZnCl2, InCl3 and TAA in the presence of preformed CQDs with the dimension of 2.1 nm (Supporting Fig. S1
                     ). The XRD patterns of all the as-obtained products show 2 θ peak at values of 21.5°, 27.6°, 30.4°, 39.8°, 47.2°, 52.4° and 55.6°, in agreement with the (0 0 6), (1 0 2), (1 0 4), (1 0 8), (1 1 0), (1 1 6) and (0 2 2) crystallographic planes of hexagonal ZnIn2S4 (JCPDS-03-065-2023) (Fig. 1
                     ). Although no diffraction peaks corresponding to CQDs is observed, the FT-IR spectra of the products shows strong peaks at 1563 cm−1 and 1397 cm−1 corresponding to the -COO- stretching vibrations, as well as a strong peak at about 3500 cm−1 assignable to the -OH stretching vibrations of CQDs, indicating the presence of the CQDs in the nanocomposites (Supporting Fig. S2). The absence of the diffraction peak corresponding to graphitic structure of CQDs (29.9°) may be due to its possible overlap with the diffraction peak corresponding to (1 0 2) crystallographic plane of ZnIn2S4 (27.6°) as well as its high dispersion on ZnIn2S4. The presence of CQDs in the nanocomposite was also confirmed by the XPS spectrum (Fig. 2
                     a–d). The XPS spectrum of 5.0 wt%-CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite in the C 1 s region shows three peaks at 284.5 eV, 286.5 eV and 288.4 eV, ascribable to the sp2 hybridized carbon (CC), epoxy/hydroxyl carbon (CO) and carboxy carbon (OCO), respectively. In addition to peaks in C 1 s region, peaks assigned to Zn2+ 2p (1023.7 eV and 1046.8 eV), In3+ 3d (445.4 eV and 462.6 eV) and S2− 2p (161.6 eV) are also observed. However, as compared with pure ZnIn2S4, all the above peaks shift towards higher binding energy, suggesting the existence of interaction between CQDs and ZnIn2S4 in the nanocomposites. The SEM and TEM image of 5.0 wt%-CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite clearly shows flower-like microspheres consist of large number of interwoven ultrathin nanosheets (Fig. 3
                     a and b). The morphology of CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite does not change obviously after the introduction of CQDs. An enlarged TEM image of the part illustrated by red dotted rectangle in Fig. 3b shows that the microspheres are consisted of nanosheets (Fig. 3c). In addition to clear lattice fringe spacing of 0.33 nm assigned to the (1 0 0) crystal plane of hexagonal ZnIn2S4, lattice fringe of 0.23 nm attributed to the graphitic structure of CQDs is also observed (Fig. 3d). All the characterizations indicate the successful incorporation of CQDs in the nanocomposite and there exists intimate contact between hexagonal ZnIn2S4 and CQDs. To fabricate Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4, Co(dmgH)2PyCl was loaded on the as-obtained CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposites via an impregnation method. Although the existence of Co(dmgH)2PyCl cannot be evidenced from the FT-IR spectrum due to the overlap of the peak of CQDs (1563 cm−1) and that of Co(dmgH)2PyCl (1561 cm−1) (Supporting Fig. S2), its presence in the nanocomposite was confirmed from both the XPS and the EDX results. In addition to showing peaks at 781.7 eV and 796.9 eV, corresponding to Co 2p in Co3+ (Fig. 2e), the XPS in N 1 s region shows peaks at 399.9 eV, confirming the existence of N element (Fig. 2f). In addition, the EDX of 1.0 wt%-Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 shows the presence of elements of Co and N in the nanocomposite (Supporting Fig. S3).

Based on the above observations, the mechanism for the enhanced photocatalytic hydrogen evolution over Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite can be proposed (Scheme 1
                     ). When ZnIn2S4 is irradiated, photo-generated electrons and holes are generated. Since the CB of CQDs is less negative than that of hexagonal ZnIn2S4, a directional transfer of the photo-generated electrons from ZnIn2S4 to CQDs is feasible [29–30]. Resulted from CQDs’ excellent properties for electrons transfer [61–62,66] and its more negative reduction potential −0.87 V vs. NHE (Supporting Fig. S6), the photo-generated electrons can transfer to Co(dmgH)2PyCl, which act as catalytic active sites for hydrogen evolution [39,64–65]. In such a ternary Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite, ZnIn2S4 acts as a photosensitizer to generate electrons and holes, while CQDs act as a bridge to promote the photogenerated electrons transfer from ZnIn2S4 
                     [67] to Co(dmgH)2PyCl [64–65], which acts as a good cocatalyst for hydrogen evolution. The effectiveness of the electron transfer from ZnIn2S4 to Co(dmgH)2PyCl is influenced by the interaction among the three components in ternary Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 as well as the electronic conductivity of the nanocomposite. Controlled experiment revealed that a mechanical mixture of ZnIn2S4, CQDs and Co(dmgH)2PyCl showed an inferior activity for hydrogen evolution, with 51.7 μmol of hydrogen evolved in 8 h. In addition, only 113.4 μmol of hydrogen was evolved in 8 h over a mixture of CQDs/ZnIn2S4 and Co(dmgH)2PyCl, as compared with 703.9 μmol over Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 nanocomposite (Supporting Fig. S7). This indicates that the superior performance over Co/CQDs/ZnIn2S4 should be ascribed to the synergistic effect of CQDs and Co(dmgH)2PyCl. Such synergistic effect has been observed in various high-performance cocatalyst-modified photocatalytic materials, mainly dual cocatalyst-modified photocatalysts, leading to rapid electron transfer and efficient interfacial catalysis [68–70]. Surely, CQDs can also act as a cocatalyst for promoting the photocatalytic hydrogen evolution. However, the hydrogen evolved via this pathway is relatively limited since as compared with CQDs, Co(dmgH)2PyCl is a much better cocatalyst for hydrogen evolution over ZnIn2S4.

